06653nam a22010455i 9789048544448DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485444487 a10.1515/97890485444482doi  a(DE-B1597)571773  a(OCoLC)1248759438  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aGT3286.T56bD43 2020 7aPOL0450002bisacsh04aThe Dead as Ancestors, Martyrs, and Heroes in Timor-Leste /ced. by Rui Feijo, Lia Kent. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (326 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPart I Ancestors, Martyrs and Heroes -- t1 Ancestors and Martyrs in Timor-Leste -- t2 Remembering the Martyrs of National Liberation in Timor-Leste -- tPart II The Dead in Everyday Life -- t3 Spirits Live Among Us -- t4 ‘Sempre la’o ho ita’ -- t5 Unfulfilled Peace -- t6 The Politics of Loss and Restoration -- t7 Death Across the Border and the Prospects of Improved People to People Relationships -- t8 Working for the Living and the Dead -- tPART III The Dead and the Nation-State -- t9 Remembering the Dead in Post-Independence Timor-Leste -- t10 Gender, Agency and the (In)Visibility of the Dead and the Wounded -- t11 On the Politics of Memory -- t12 Gathering the Dead, Imagining the State? -- t13 Selling Names -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the 24-year Indonesian occupation of Timor-Leste, thousands of people died or were killed in circumstances that did not allow the required death rituals to be performed at the time. Since the country attained independence in 1999, families have consequently devoted significant time, effort and resources to fulfilling their obligations to the dead. These obligations are accorded particular significance due to the fact that the dead are ascribed agency and can play a benevolent or malevolent role in the lives of the living. Such grassroots initiatives run in parallel with, and reveal a range of different attitudes towards, official initiatives that seek to transform particular dead bodies into public symbols of heroism, sacrifice and nationhood. This book focuses on the dynamic interplay between the potent presence of the dead in everyday life and their symbolic usefulness in wider processes of state and nation formation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDeathxSocial aspectszTimor-Leste. 0aFuneral rites and ceremonieszTimor-Leste. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHeritage Studies. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aSouth East Asia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Colonialism & Post-Colonialism.2bisacsh  aThe dead.  aTimor-Leste.  aancestors.  aheroes.  aidentity narratives.  aimagining nation and state.  amartyrs.1 aBlau, Soren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoarccaech, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamaledo, Andrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeijo, Rui, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGraça Feijó, Rui, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrenfell, Damian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKent, Lia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKent, Lia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKumala Sakti, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeach, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatos Viegas, Susana de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re